This is posted on our internal Yammer

>>> May is Mental Health Awareness Month, In honor of this, I share my Story:
To Hell and Back:

My first episode of major depression was when I was a junior in high school. The love of my life cheated and broke my heart. It lasted 6-12 months and then resolved on its own. Since then I’ve endured 8-10 episodes of major depression. When I was a teenager and in my early twenties I was offered no treatment. I self treated with cannibus. When I got a job at Northwestern Mutual after college I learned there were medications that could help. Since that time, I’ve been on nearly every medication on the market. SSRI’s (Prozac, Celexa, Lexapro and Viibryd, SNRI’s (Cymbalta, Effexor and Pristiq), Tricyclics (Nortriptyline and Desipramine) and atypical antidepressants such as Serzone, Wellbutrin, Oleptro, Remeron and Trazadone. Some even helped for years. Wisconsin needs to legalize medical marijuana. Ive read a 50/50 combo of THC/CBD works the best. I’m denied this medication because I live where its not legal. I do use CBD oil for anxiety and chronic pain. It’s helpful! My Dr. knows and approves.

Most of the medications made me very hungry and I gained 30 pounds in-spite of a rigorous diet and exercise plan. I never liked how I looked and now I was fat and ugly and developed sleep apnea for which I need to use a CPAP machine to this day. Now I felt unloveable!

Two years ago medications quit working for me and I developed treatment resistant depression. Over the past two years I’ve tried several more antidepressants, antipsychotics mood stabilizers and they did not work. The nurse practitioner I was seeing talked me into doing electroconvulsive therapy ECT. For those who don’t know this treatment is done in the hospital under general anesthesia. They shock your brain and induce a seizure. It’s supposed to be the most effective treatment for depression there is. I went three days a week for a month. It wasn’t working so I wound up in the hospital again. There I was started on Pristiq which had worked for me in the past. I also received ECT once a week for a month. I did experience memory loss from the procedure but with the help of the combo of ECT and medication I was able to return to work.

>>> I had missed three months of work when doing ECT. It was tough to re-acclimate due to the memory loss I’d experienced. I was better but the problem was the medications made me extremely tired. I had a hard time staying up till 8 o clock and got through my days with lots of caffeine. I pleaded with my provider to give me something else and she refused. I got depressed again. This time I was hopeless, I had tried everything including ECT. It was now time to give up. I took my belt from my dresser and tried to wedge it in the bathroom door to hang myself. It didn’t work. I was too stupid to figure out how to kill myself how much more of a failure could I be?

Two days later I was at work. We had a team meeting and I started crying uncontrollably for no reason. I did that a lot back then. I called my Dr and she told me to go to the hospital. They switched Pristiq to Viibrtd and advised I get Dialectical Behavior Therapy, DBT. They offered that at Rogers hospital so I signed up. It was four hours of group therapy a day plus a once a week consult with a psychiatrist. It turns out that the medication they put me on when I was in the hospital made me too sick to continue. Now what?

With the help of my wife, the psychiatrist at Rogers and my own research skills, I honed being a disability insurance underwriter at Northwestern Mutual for the past 21 years, I decided to try a little used MAOI inhibitor called Parnate. Less than 1% of antidepressant prescriptions are for MAOI Inhibitors. To go on that medication you need to be off all antidepressants for two weeks. Otherwise there is the risk of serotonin toxicity which can be fatal. They tapered me off my medications rather quickly and I had serotonin discontinuation syndrome which basically made me feel like shit for two weeks. I was dizzy, had brain shocks the whole catastrophe. I started Parnate and developed nausea, insomnia, dizziness, erectile dysfunction and delayed orgasm. Now I was scared since I believed this was really my final option. I ended up in the hospital again with intense suicidal thoughts.

MAOI inhibitors were the first generation antidepressant. However they fell out of favor with psychiatrists due to their potentially lethal interaction with common foods such as aged cheese and meats as well as many medications. They now make up less than 1% of antidepresssant prescriptions in-spite of the fact they are the most effective antidepresssants and target dopamine, serotonin and norepinephrine. Modern antidepressants do not have the effectiveness of the MAOI but are also not as toxic.

I decided to continue with the meds to see if the side effects would resolve. They actually got worse as did my anxiety when my psychiatrist increased my Parnate dose in hopes of getting my depression in remission. When he told me a week later to go back down on dose I was ready to throw in the towel. I calmly told my wife I was going to Home Depot to get some rope to hang myself in the basement. I could not take it anymore. She freaked out, took my car keys and wouldn’t let me leave the house. She asked me why I wanted to kill myself and I didn’t have a good reason so she talked me into talking to the psychiatrist again to make sure I was really out of options. I agreed. I didn’t really want to die I wanted the pain and emptiness to go away.

>>> I believed I was unloveable and no one would care anyways. My wife Carla would get over me in a couple weeks and go on without me. After discussing my options with Dr. Holloway we decided to add a low dose of Vraylar to the Parnate. How am I doing now? Awesome! I’m on Parnate and a small dose of Vraylar and I no longer suffer from anxiety or depression. I still have frustrating sexual side effects and insomnia. I take Alprazalam for sleep, Viagra for erectyle dysfunction and plan to try Ginko Bilbao for orgasm delay. I no longer have nausea and I no longer have a painful bladder disorder, Interstitial Cystitis, IC. Many with IC have committed suicide since there is no cure and no good treatment. It feels like a constant UTI or Prostatis with pain and frequency sometimes up to 30 times per day. The SSRI’s and SNRIs tended to flare my IC which is why my treatment options became limited. I feel so happy to be alive and so grateful for everyone who has helped me in any way. To those who have helped in any small way, from telling me I matter to driving me to the hospital, you saved my life. I don’t share this story for pity, I share for inspiration. Please share, I want as many people to see this as possible. My story could save someone else’s life and if I can do that my struggle will have been worth it.
